      explanation: `## Detailed Pathophysiology

### Pulmonary Injury
- Water aspiration volumes typically 1-3 mL/kg
- Surfactant dysfunction (fresh and salt water)
- Alveolar edema
- Loss of functional residual capacity
- Intrapulmonary shunting

### Cardiovascular
- Hypoxia-induced bradycardia
- Arrhythmias
- Cardiac arrest (asystole/PEA)
- Cold water: vagal responses

### Neurological
- Time to hypoxic injury: 4-6 minutes
- Cerebral edema
- Selective neuronal vulnerability
- Hypothermia may be protective

## Resuscitation Approach

### In-Water Rescue
- In-water rescue breaths if trained
- Horizontal extrication
- Minimize C-spine manipulation unless trauma

### CPR Modifications
- 5 initial rescue breaths
- Then standard CPR ratio
- Prolonged resuscitation if hypothermic
- Early advanced airway

### Prognostication
- Submersion time >25 min: poor prognosis
- Cold water may improve outcomes
- Pupil response unreliable if cold`,
